    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/8682776-erin">Erin</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer17265030246599056083">As a huge Greene fan, I&apos;ve always felt this one was important, rather than truly first rate. It has some brilliant paragraphs and your first sentence </span>
  <span id="freeText17265030246599056083" style="display:none">As a huge Greene fan, I've always felt this one was important, rather than truly first rate. It has some brilliant paragraphs and your first sentence of the review is quite true. Certainly reading a number of other fictional attempts at prophecy on complicated situations in other countries (South Africa, Colombia, Bosnia, etc.) has made me appreciate how tricky it is to do properly, and reading plenty of fiction and non-fiction about Vietnam from 1945-1986 has made me realize what an outlier Greeneland still is, even in terms of scene-setting. But there's something about this one that makes it ring in my memory less than, say, the great 40s triumvirate of The Power and the Glory, The Heart of the Matter and the screenplay of The Third Man, or my later favourites, The Comedians and The Human Factor. Maybe it's what you say about Phuong? Something a little ultimately heartless about it, perhaps. But I read it last 24 years ago, I think, so perhaps it's time for a re-visit.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17265030246599056083" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

