<span id="freeTextContainer10589424796627173669"><b>To be in love is to see yourself as someone else sees you, it is to be in love with the falsified and exalted image of yourself.</b><br/><br/>Have you ever read a book at one time and hated it only to love it years later when you pick it up again? That has happened to me twice. Once with The Great Gatsby and now this novel. When I read it the second time, I fell in love with the narrative voice and was enticed into finding out how it all comes out in the end. I&apos;m glad I did. I liked all the characters. Everyo</span>
  <span id="freeText10589424796627173669" style="display:none"><b>To be in love is to see yourself as someone else sees you, it is to be in love with the falsified and exalted image of yourself.</b><br /><br />Have you ever read a book at one time and hated it only to love it years later when you pick it up again? That has happened to me twice. Once with The Great Gatsby and now this novel. When I read it the second time, I fell in love with the narrative voice and was enticed into finding out how it all comes out in the end. I'm glad I did. I liked all the characters. Everyone from the cynical main character, Fowler; the alluring Phuong and naive Pyle all captivated my attention and I was sad to say goodbye to them as I closed the book. I plan on reading more Graham Greene in the future. A solid 4 out of 5 from me.<br /><br /><b>Suffering is not increased by numbers: one body can contain all the suffering the world can feel.</b></span>
